class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tyler%27s_tree_frog">/wiki/Tyler%27s_tree_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Tyler<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#39;</span>s tree frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Tyler's tree frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Litoria tyleri</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) has large toe pads and webbed feet.</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2644"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The muscular system has been similarly modified. The hind limbs of ancestral frogs presumably contained pairs of muscles which would act in opposition (one muscle to flex the knee, a different muscle to extend it), as is seen in most other limbed animals. However, in modern frogs, almost all muscles have been modified to contribute to the action of jumping, with only a few small muscles remaining to bring the limb back to the starting position and maintain posture. The muscles have also been greatly enlarged, with the main leg muscles accounting for over 17% of the total mass of frogs.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Frogjump_53-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Frogjump-53">#cite_note-Frogjump-53</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>53</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2645"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Many frogs have webbed feet and the degree of webbing is directly proportional to the amount of time the species spends in the water.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Exploratorium_54-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Exploratorium-54">#cite_note-Exploratorium-54</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>54</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The completely aquatic </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/African_dwarf_frog">/wiki/African_dwarf_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">African dwarf frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>African dwarf frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Hymenochirus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span> sp.) has fully webbed toes, whereas those of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White%27s_tree_frog">/wiki/White%27s_tree_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">White<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#39;</span>s tree frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>White's tree frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Litoria caerulea</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>), an arboreal species, are only a quarter or half webbed.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-55</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-55">#cite_note-55</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>55</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Exceptions include </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flying_frog">/wiki/Flying_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Flying frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>flying frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hylidae">/wiki/Hylidae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hylidae</a>"&gt;</span><span>Hylidae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhacophoridae">/wiki/Rhacophoridae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Rhacophoridae</a>"&gt;</span><span>Rhacophoridae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, which also have fully webbed toes used in gliding.
</span></span><span id="line2646"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tree_frog">/wiki/Tree_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Tree frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Arboreal frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> have pads located on the ends of their toes to help grip vertical surfaces. These are not suction pads, the surface consisting instead of columnar cells with flat tops with small gaps between them lubricated by mucous glands. When the frog applies pressure, the cells adhere to irregularities on the surface and the grip is maintained through </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capillarity">/wiki/Capillarity</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Capillarity</a>"&gt;</span><span>surface tension</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. This allows the frog to climb on smooth surfaces, but the system does not function efficiently when the pads are excessively wet.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-56</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-56">#cite_note-56</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>56</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2647"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>In many arboreal frogs, a small "intercalary structure" on each toe increases the surface area touching the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Substrate_(biology)">/wiki/Substrate_(biology)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Substrate (biology)</a>"&gt;</span><span>substrate</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Furthermore, many arboreal frogs have hip joints that allow both hopping and walking. Some frogs that live high in trees even possess an elaborate degree of webbing between their toes. This allows the frogs to "parachute" or make a controlled glide from one position in the canopy to another.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-57</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-57">#cite_note-57</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>57</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2648"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Ground-dwelling frogs generally lack the adaptations of aquatic and arboreal frogs. Most have smaller toe pads, if any, and little webbing. Some burrowing frogs such as </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Couch%27s_Spadefoot_Toad">/wiki/Couch%27s_Spadefoot_Toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Couch<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#39;</span>s Spadefoot Toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>Couch's spadefoot</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Scaphiopus couchii</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) have a flap-like toe extension on the hind feet, a </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keratin">/wiki/Keratin</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Keratin</a>"&gt;</span><span>keratinised</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tubercle">/wiki/Tubercle</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Tubercle</a>"&gt;</span><span>tubercle</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> often referred to as a spade, that helps them to burrow.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-58</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-58">#cite_note-58</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>58</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2649"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Sometimes during the tadpole stage, one of the developing rear legs is eaten by a predator such as a </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dragonfly_nymph">/wiki/Dragonfly_nymph</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Dragonfly nymph</a>"&gt;</span><span>dragonfly nymph</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. In some cases, the full leg still grows, but in others it does not, although the frog may still live out its normal lifespan with only three limbs. Occasionally, a parasitic </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flatworm">/wiki/Flatworm</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Flatworm</a>"&gt;</span><span>flatworm</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ribeiroia_ondatrae">/wiki/Ribeiroia_ondatrae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Ribeiroia ondatrae</a>"&gt;</span><span>Ribeiroia ondatrae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) digs into the rear of a tadpole, causing a rearrangement of the limb bud cells and the frog develops one or more extra legs.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-59</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-59">#cite_note-59</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>59</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2650"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2651"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size mw-halign-left</a>" <span class="attribute-name">typeof</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw:File/Thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-file-description</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">img</span> <span class="attribute-name">src</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Ranapipiensmoulting.jpg/220px-Ranapipiensmoulting.jpg">//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Ranapipiensmoulting.jpg/220px-Ranapipiensmoulting.jpg</a>" <span class="attribute-name">decoding</span>="<a class="attribute-value">async</a>" <span class="attribute-name">width</span>="<a class="attribute-value">220</a>" <span class="attribute-name">height</span>="<a class="attribute-value">165</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-file-element</a>" <span //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f1/Ranapipiensmoulting.jpg/440px-Ranapipiensmoulting.jpg 2x</a>" <span class="attribute-name">data-file-width</span>="<a class="attribute-value">3648</a>" <span class="attribute-name">data-file-height</span>="<a class="attribute-value">2736</a>" <span>/</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_leopard_frog">/wiki/Northern_leopard_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Northern leopard frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Northern leopard frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana pipiens</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) moulting and eating its skin</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2652"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Skin</a>"&gt;</span><span>Skin</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2653"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>A frog's skin is protective, has a respiratory function, can absorb water, and helps control body temperature. It has many glands, particularly on the head and back, which often exude distasteful and toxic substances (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skin">/wiki/Skin</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Skin</a>"&gt;</span><span>granular glands</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>). The secretion is often sticky and helps keep the skin moist, protects against the entry of moulds and bacteria, and makes the animal slippery and more able to escape from predators.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-60</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-60">#cite_note-60</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>60</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The skin is shed every few weeks. It usually splits down the middle of the back and across the belly, and the frog pulls its arms and legs free. The sloughed skin is then worked towards the head where it is quickly eaten.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-61</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-61">#cite_note-61</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>61</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2654"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Being cold-blooded, frogs have to adopt suitable behaviour patterns to regulate their temperature. To warm up, they can move into the sun or onto a warm surface; if they overheat, they can move into the shade or adopt a stance that exposes the minimum area of skin to the air. This posture is also used to prevent water loss and involves the frog squatting close to the substrate with its hands and feet tucked under its chin and body.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-BandN_62-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-BandN-62">#cite_note-BandN-62</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>62</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The colour of a frog's skin is used for thermoregulation. In cool damp conditions, the colour will be darker than on a hot dry day. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grey_Foam-nest_Treefrog">/wiki/Grey_Foam-nest_Treefrog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Grey Foam-nest Treefrog</a>"&gt;</span><span>grey foam-nest tree frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Chiromantis xerampelina</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) is even able to turn white to minimise the chance of overheating.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-63</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-63">#cite_note-63</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>63</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2655"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Many frogs are able to absorb water and oxygen directly through the skin, especially around the pelvic area, but the permeability of a frog's skin can also result in water loss. Glands located all over the body exude mucus which helps keep the skin moist and reduces evaporation. Some glands on the hands and chest of males are specialised to produce sticky secretions to aid in </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amplexus">/wiki/Amplexus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Amplexus</a>"&gt;</span><span>amplexus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Similar glands in tree frogs produce a glue-like substance on the adhesive discs of the feet. Some arboreal frogs reduce water loss by having a waterproof layer of skin, and several South American species coat their skin with a waxy secretion. Other frogs have adopted behaviours to conserve water, including becoming </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nocturnal">/wiki/Nocturnal</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Nocturnal</a>"&gt;</span><span>nocturnal</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and resting in a water-conserving position. Some frogs may also rest in large groups with each frog pressed against its neighbours. This reduces the amount of skin exposed to the air or a dry surface, and thus reduces water loss.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-BandN_62-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-BandN-62">#cite_note-BandN-62</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>62</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woodhouse%27s_toad">/wiki/Woodhouse%27s_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Woodhouse<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#39;</span>s toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>Woodhouse's toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Bufo woodhousii</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>), if given access to water after confinement in a dry location, sits in the shallows to rehydrate.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-64</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-64">#cite_note-64</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>64</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The male </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hairy_frog">/wiki/Hairy_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hairy frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>hairy frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Trichobatrachus robustus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) has </span><span>&lt;<span </span></span><span id="line2660"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camouflage">/wiki/Camouflage</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Camouflage</a>"&gt;</span><span>Camouflage</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> is a common defensive mechanism in frogs. Features such as warts and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skin_fold">/wiki/Skin_fold</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Skin fold</a>"&gt;</span><span>skin folds</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> are usually on ground-dwelling frogs, for whom smooth skin would not provide such effective camouflage. Certain frogs change colour between night and day, as light and moisture stimulate the pigment cells and cause them to expand or contract.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Observer_69-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a skin (dorsolateral dermal plica) similar to a leaf </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" stripes similar to fallen leaf features.
</span></span><span id="line2661"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2662"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Respiration_and_circulation</a>"&gt;</span><span>Respiration and circulation</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2663"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Like other amphibians, </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxygen">/wiki/Oxygen</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Oxygen</a>"&gt;</span><span>oxygen</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> can pass through their highly permeable skins. This unique feature allows them to remain in places without access to the air, respiring through their skins. Ribs are generally absent, so the lungs are filled by </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buccal_pumping">/wiki/Buccal_pumping</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Buccal pumping</a>"&gt;</span><span>buccal pumping</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and a frog deprived of its lungs can maintain its body functions without them.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Observer_69-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Observer-69">#cite_note-Observer-69</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The fully aquatic </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bornean_flat-headed_frog">/wiki/Bornean_flat-headed_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Bornean flat-headed frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Bornean flat-headed frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> entirely.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-72</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a </span></span><span id="line2664"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs have three-chambered </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heart">/wiki/Heart</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Heart</a>"&gt;</span><span>hearts</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, a feature they share with </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lizard">/wiki/Lizard</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Lizard</a>"&gt;</span><span>lizards</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Oxygenated blood from the lungs and de-oxygenated blood from the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Respiration_(physiology)">/wiki/Respiration_(physiology)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Respiration (physiology)</a>"&gt;</span><span>respiring</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> tissues enter the heart through separate </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atrium_(anatomy)">/wiki/Atrium_(anatomy)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Atrium (anatomy)</a>"&gt;</span><span>atria</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. When these chambers contract, the two blood streams pass into a common </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ventricle_(heart)">/wiki/Ventricle_(heart)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Ventricle (heart)</a>"&gt;</span><span>ventricle</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> before being pumped via a spiral valve to the appropriate vessel, the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aorta">/wiki/Aorta</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Aorta</a>"&gt;</span><span>aorta</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> for oxygenated blood and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pulmonary_artery">/wiki/Pulmonary_artery</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Pulmonary artery</a>"&gt;</span><span>pulmonary artery</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> for deoxygenated blood.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span </span></span><span id="line2665"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Some species of frog have adaptations that allow them to survive in oxygen deficient water. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Titicaca_water_frog">/wiki/Titicaca_water_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Titicaca water frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Titicaca water frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Telmatobius culeus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) is one such species and has  wrinkly skin that increases its surface area to enhance gas exchange. It normally makes no use of its rudimentary lungs but will sometimes raise and lower its body rhythmically while on the lake bed to increase the flow of water around it.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-74</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-74">#cite_note-74</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>74</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>

</span></span><span id="line2668"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Digestion_and_excretion</a>"&gt;</span><span>Digestion and excretion</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2669"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs have maxillary teeth along their upper jaw which are used to hold food before it is swallowed. These teeth are very weak, and cannot be used to chew or catch and harm agile prey. Instead, the frog uses its sticky, cleft tongue to catch insects and other small moving prey. The tongue normally lies coiled in the mouth, free at the back and attached to the mandible at the front. It can be shot out and retracted at great speed.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Exploratorium_54-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Exploratorium-54">#cite_note-Exploratorium-54</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>54</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> In amphibians there are salvary glands on the tongue, which in frogs produce what is called a two-phase viscoelastic fluid. When exposed to pressure, like when the tongue is wrapping around a prey, it becomes runny and covers the prey's body. As the pressure drops, it returns to a thick and elastic state, which gives the tongue an extra grip.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-75</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-75">#cite_note-75</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Some frogs have no tongue and just stuff food into their mouths with their hands.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a jaw which function like teeth.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Pou92_16-1</a>" <span skull and help push food down the throat.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Exploratorium_54-3</a>" <span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2670"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The food then moves through the oesophagus into the stomach where digestive enzymes are added and it is churned up. It then proceeds to the small intestine (duodenum and ileum) where most digestion occurs. Pancreatic juice from the pancreas, and bile, produced by the liver and stored in the gallbladder, are secreted into the small intestine, where the fluids digest the food and the nutrients are absorbed. The food residue passes into the large intestine where excess water is removed and the wastes are passed out through the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cloaca">/wiki/Cloaca</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cloaca</a>"&gt;</span><span>cloaca</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-77</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-77">#cite_note-77</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>77</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2671"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Although adapted to terrestrial life, frogs resemble freshwater fish in their inability to conserve body water effectively. When they are on land, much water is lost by evaporation from the skin. The excretory system is similar to that of mammals and there are two </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kidney">/wiki/Kidney</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Kidney</a>"&gt;</span><span>kidneys</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> that remove nitrogenous products from the blood. Frogs produce large quantities of dilute urine in order to flush out toxic products from the kidney tubules.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Doritexcretion_78-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" terrestrial adults. A few species of tree frog with little access to water excrete the even less toxic </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a All bodily wastes exit the body through the cloaca which terminates in a cloacal vent.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-TutorVista_79-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-TutorVista-79">#cite_note-TutorVista-79</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>79</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>

</span></span><span id="line2675"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>In the male frog, the two </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Testis">/wiki/Testis</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Testis</a>"&gt;</span><span>testes</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> are attached to the kidneys and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semen">/wiki/Semen</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Semen</a>"&gt;</span><span>semen</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> passes into the kidneys through fine tubes called </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Efferent_ducts">/wiki/Efferent_ducts</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Efferent ducts</a>"&gt;</span><span>efferent ducts</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. It then travels on through the ureters, which are consequently known as urinogenital ducts. There is no penis, and sperm is ejected from the cloaca directly onto the eggs as the female lays them. The ovaries of the female frog are beside the kidneys and the eggs pass down a pair of oviducts and through the cloaca to the exterior.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-TutorVista_79-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-TutorVista-79">#cite_note-TutorVista-79</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>79</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2676"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>When frogs mate, the male climbs on the back of the female and wraps his fore limbs round her body, either behind the front legs or just in front of the hind legs. This position is called </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amplexus">/wiki/Amplexus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Amplexus</a>"&gt;</span><span>amplexus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and may be held for several days.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-80</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a characteristics</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. These include  the development of special pads on his thumbs in the breeding season, to give him a firm hold.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-81</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-81">#cite_note-81</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>81</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The grip of the male frog during amplexus stimulates the female to release eggs, usually wrapped in jelly, as spawn. In many species the male is smaller and slimmer than the female. Males have vocal cords and make a range of croaks, particularly in the breeding season, and in some species they also have </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vocal_sac">/wiki/Vocal_sac</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Vocal sac</a>"&gt;</span><span>vocal sacs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> to amplify the sound.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-TutorVista_79-2</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-TutorVista-79">#cite_note-TutorVista-79</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>79</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2677"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2678"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Nervous_system</a>"&gt;</span><span>Nervous system</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2679"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs have a highly developed nervous system that consists of a brain, spinal cord and nerves. Many parts of frog brains correspond with those of humans. It consists of two olfactory lobes, two cerebral hemispheres, a pineal body, two optic lobes, a cerebellum and a medulla oblongata. Muscular coordination and posture are controlled by the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebellum">/wiki/Cerebellum</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cerebellum</a>"&gt;</span><span>cerebellum</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, and the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Medulla_oblongata">/wiki/Medulla_oblongata</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Medulla oblongata</a>"&gt;</span><span>medulla oblongata</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> regulates respiration, digestion and other automatic functions. The relative size of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cerebrum">/wiki/Cerebrum</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cerebrum</a>"&gt;</span><span>cerebrum</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in frogs is much smaller than it is in humans. Frogs have ten pairs of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cranial_nerves">/wiki/Cranial_nerves</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cranial nerves</a>"&gt;</span><span>cranial nerves</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> which pass information from the outside directly to the brain, and ten pairs of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spinal_nerves">/wiki/Spinal_nerves</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Spinal nerves</a>"&gt;</span><span>spinal nerves</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> which pass information from the extremities to the brain through the spinal cord.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>  By contrast, all </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amniotes">/wiki/Amniotes</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (mammals, birds and reptiles) have twelve pairs of cranial nerves.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span </span></span><span id="line2681"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size mw-halign-left</a>" </span></span><span id="line2683"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The eyes of most frogs are located on either side of the head near the top and project outwards as hemispherical bulges. They provide </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Binocular_vision">/wiki/Binocular_vision</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Binocular vision</a>"&gt;</span><span>binocular vision</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> over a field of 100° to the front and a total visual field of almost 360°.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Howard_83-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Howard-83">#cite_note-Howard-83</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>83</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> They may be the only part of an otherwise submerged frog to protrude from the water. Each eye has closable upper and lower lids and a </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nictitating_membrane">/wiki/Nictitating_membrane</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Nictitating membrane</a>"&gt;</span><span>nictitating membrane</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> which provides further protection, especially when the frog is swimming.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Badger_84-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Pipidae</a>"&gt;</span><span>Pipidae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> have the eyes located at the top of the head, a position better suited for detecting prey in the water above.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Howard_83-1</a>" <span The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" The irises of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southern_toad">/wiki/Southern_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Southern toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>southern toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Anaxyrus terrestris</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) are patterned so as to blend in with the surrounding camouflaged skin.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Badger_84-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Badger-84">#cite_note-Badger-84</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>84</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2684"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The distant vision of a frog is better than its near vision. Calling frogs will quickly become silent when they see an intruder or even a moving shadow but the closer an object is, the less well it is seen.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> </span></span><span id="line2689"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs can hear both in the air and below water. They do not have </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pinna_(anatomy)">/wiki/Pinna_(anatomy)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Pinna (anatomy)</a>"&gt;</span><span>external ears</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>; the eardrums (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tympanum_(anatomy)">/wiki/Tympanum_(anatomy)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Tympanum (anatomy)</a>"&gt;</span><span>tympanic membranes</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>) are directly exposed or may be covered by a layer of skin and are visible as a circular area just behind the eye. The size and distance apart of the eardrums is related to the frequency and wavelength at which the frog calls. In some species such as the bullfrog, the size of the tympanum indicates the sex of the frog; males have tympani that are larger than their eyes while in females, the eyes and tympani are much the same size.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Neth38_87-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Neth38-87">#cite_note-Neth38-87</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>87</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> A noise causes the tympanum to vibrate and the sound is transmitted to the middle and inner ear. The middle ear contains semicircular canals which help control balance and orientation. In the inner ear, the auditory hair cells are arranged in two areas of the cochlea, the basilar papilla and the amphibian papilla. The former detects high frequencies and the latter low frequencies.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_tuning">/wiki/Electrical_tuning</a>" <span </span></span><span id="line2695"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The call or croak of a frog is unique to its species. Frogs create this sound by passing air through the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Larynx">/wiki/Larynx</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Larynx</a>"&gt;</span><span>larynx</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in the throat. In most calling frogs, the sound is amplified by one or more vocal sacs, membranes of skin under the throat or on the corner of the mouth, that distend during the amplification of the call. Some frog calls are so loud that they can be heard up to a mile (1.6</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">nowrap</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>km) away.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-90</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-90">#cite_note-90</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>90</span><span>&lt;<span </span></span><span id="line2696"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The main function of calling is for male frogs to attract mates. Males may call individually or there may be a chorus of sound where numerous males have converged on breeding sites. In many frog species, such as the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_Tree_Frog">/wiki/Common_Tree_Frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span to reinforce reproductive activity in a breeding colony.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-93</a>" <span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Female frogs prefer males that produce sounds of greater intensity and lower frequency, attributes that stand out in a crowd. The rationale for this is thought to be that by demonstrating his prowess, the male shows his fitness to produce superior offspring.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-94</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-94">#cite_note-94</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>94</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
