torrent frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Concave-eared torrent frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Amolops tormotus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) are unusual in many aspects. The males are notable for their varieties of calls where upward and downward frequency modulations take place. When they communicate, they produce calls that fall in the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ultrasound">/wiki/Ultrasound</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Ultrasound</a>"&gt;</span><span>ultrasound</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> frequency range. The last aspect that makes this species of frog's calls unusual is that nonlinear acoustic phenomena are important components in their acoustic signals.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-ultrasonic_99-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-ultrasonic-99">#cite_note-ultrasonic-99</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>99</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2701"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2702"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Torpor</a>"&gt;</span><span>Torpor</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2703"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>During extreme conditions, some frogs enter a state of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Torpor">/wiki/Torpor</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Torpor</a>"&gt;</span><span>torpor</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and remain inactive for months. In colder regions, many species of frog </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hibernation">/wiki/Hibernation</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hibernation</a>"&gt;</span><span>hibernate</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in winter. Those that live on land such as the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_toad">/wiki/American_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">American toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>American toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Bufo americanus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) dig a burrow and make a </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hibernaculum_(zoology)">/wiki/Hibernaculum_(zoology)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hibernaculum (zoology)</a>"&gt;</span><span>hibernaculum</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in which to lie </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dormancy">/wiki/Dormancy</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Dormancy</a>"&gt;</span><span>dormant</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Others, less proficient at digging, find a crevice or bury themselves in dead leaves. Aquatic species such as the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_bullfrog">/wiki/American_bullfrog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">American bullfrog</a>"&gt;</span><span>American bullfrog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana catesbeiana</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) normally sink to the bottom of the pond where they lie, semi-immersed in mud but still able to access the oxygen dissolved in the water. Their metabolism slows down and they live on their energy reserves. Some frogs such as the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wood_frog">/wiki/Wood_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Wood frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>wood frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moor_frog">/wiki/Moor_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Moor frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>moor frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, or </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spring_peeper">/wiki/Spring_peeper</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Spring peeper</a>"&gt;</span><span>spring peeper</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> can even survive being frozen. Ice crystals form under the skin and in the body cavity but the essential organs are protected from freezing by a high concentration of glucose. An apparently lifeless, frozen frog can resume respiration and its heartbeat can restart when conditions warm up.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-100</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-100">#cite_note-100</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>100</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2704"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>At the other extreme, the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Striped_burrowing_frog">/wiki/Striped_burrowing_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Striped burrowing frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>striped burrowing frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Cyclorana alboguttata</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) regularly </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aestivation">/wiki/Aestivation</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Aestivation</a>"&gt;</span><span>aestivates</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> during the hot, dry season in Australia, surviving in a dormant state without access to food and water for nine or ten months of the year. It burrows underground and curls up inside a protective </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cocoon_(silk)">/wiki/Cocoon_(silk)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cocoon (silk)</a>"&gt;</span><span>cocoon</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> formed by its shed skin. Researchers at the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Queensland">/wiki/University_of_Queensland</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">University of Queensland</a>"&gt;</span><span>University of Queensland</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> have found that during aestivation, the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metabolism">/wiki/Metabolism</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Metabolism</a>"&gt;</span><span>metabolism</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> of the frog is altered and the operational efficiency of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mitochondria">/wiki/Mitochondria</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Mitochondria</a>"&gt;</span><span>mitochondria</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> is increased. This means that the limited amount of energy available to the comatose frog is used in a more efficient manner. This survival mechanism is only useful to animals that remain completely unconscious for an extended period of time and whose energy requirements are low because they are cold-blooded and have no need to generate heat.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-101</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-101">#cite_note-101</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>101</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Other research showed that, to provide these energy requirements, muscles atrophy, but hind limb muscles are preferentially unaffected.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-102</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-102">#cite_note-102</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>102</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Frogs have been found to have upper critical temperatures of around 41 degrees Celsius.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-103</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a </span></span><span id="line2706"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading2</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h2</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Locomotion</a>"&gt;</span><span>Locomotion</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h2</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2707"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Different species of frog use a number of methods of moving around including </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jumping">/wiki/Jumping</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Burrow</a>"&gt;</span><span>burrowing</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, </span><span>&lt;<span </span></span><span id="line2711"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs are generally recognised as exceptional jumpers and, relative to their size, the best jumpers of all vertebrates.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-104</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span jump.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Britannica_111-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> When they try to move rapidly, they speed up the rate of movement of their limbs or resort to an ungainly hopping gait. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Plains_narrow-mouthed_toad">/wiki/Great_Plains_narrow-mouthed_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Gastrophryne olivacea</span><span>&lt;/<span speeds. By measuring the toad's uptake of oxygen it was found that hopping was an inefficient use of resources during sustained locomotion but was a useful strategy during short bursts of high-intensity activity.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-113</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-113">#cite_note-113</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>113</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2718"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kassina_maculata">/wiki/Kassina_maculata</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Kassina maculata</a>"&gt;</span><span>red-legged running frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Kassina maculata</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) has short, slim hind limbs unsuited to jumping. It can move fast by using a running gait in which the two hind legs are used alternately. Slow-motion photography shows, unlike a horse that can trot or gallop, the frog's gait remained similar at slow, medium, and fast speeds.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span insects.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-115</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a several metres (yards).</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Badger2_107-1</a>" <span </span></span><span id="line2721"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size</a>" <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_toad">/wiki/Common_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Common toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>Common toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Bufo bufo</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) swimming</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2722"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs that live in or visit water have adaptations that improve their swimming abilities. The hind limbs are heavily muscled and strong. The webbing between the toes of the hind feet increases the area of the foot and helps propel the frog powerfully through the water. Members of the family </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipidae">/wiki/Pipidae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Pipidae</a>"&gt;</span><span>Pipidae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> are wholly aquatic and show the most marked specialisation. They have inflexible vertebral columns, flattened, streamlined bodies, </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lateral_line">/wiki/Lateral_line</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Lateral line</a>"&gt;</span><span>lateral line</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> systems, and powerful hind limbs with large webbed feet.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Pipidae_116-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Pipidae-116">#cite_note-Pipidae-116</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>116</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Tadpoles mostly have large tail fins which provide thrust when the tail is moved from side to side.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Duellman_117-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Duellman-117">#cite_note-Duellman-117</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>117</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2723"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2724"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Burrowing</a>"&gt;</span><span>Burrowing</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2725"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Some frogs have become adapted for burrowing and a life underground. They tend to have rounded bodies, short limbs, small heads with bulging eyes, and hind feet adapted for excavation. An extreme example of this is the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Purple_frog">/wiki/Purple_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Purple frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>purple frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Nasikabatrachus sahyadrensis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) from southern India which feeds on </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Termite">/wiki/Termite</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Termite</a>"&gt;</span><span>termites</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and spends almost its whole life underground. It emerges briefly during the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monsoon">/wiki/Monsoon</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Monsoon</a>"&gt;</span><span>monsoon</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> to mate and breed in temporary pools. It has a tiny head with a pointed snout and a plump, rounded body. Because of this </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fossorial">/wiki/Fossorial</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Fossorial</a>"&gt;</span><span>fossorial</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> existence, it was </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Species_description">/wiki/Species_description</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Species description</a>"&gt;</span><span>first described</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in 2003, being new to the scientific community at that time, although previously known to local people.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-118</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-118">#cite_note-118</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>118</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2726"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2727"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size mw-halign-left</a>" <span class="attribute-name">typeof</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw:File/Thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Nasikabatrachus_sahyadrensis.jpg">/wiki/File:Nasikabatrachus_sahyadrensis.jpg</a>" <span class="attribute-value">Purple frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Purple frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Nasikabatrachus sahyadrensis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>)</span><span>&lt;/<span </span></span><span id="line2728"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The spadefoot toads of North America are also adapted to underground life. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plains_spadefoot_toad">/wiki/Plains_spadefoot_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Plains spadefoot toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>Plains spadefoot toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Spea bombifrons</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) is typical and has a flap of keratinised bone attached to one of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metatarsus">/wiki/Metatarsus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Metatarsus</a>"&gt;</span><span>metatarsals</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> of the hind feet which it uses to dig itself backwards into the ground. As it digs, the toad wriggles its hips from side to side to sink into the loose soil. It has a shallow burrow in the summer from which it emerges at night to forage. In winter, it digs much deeper and has been recorded at a depth of 4.5<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>m (14<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>ft 9<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>in).</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Farrar_119-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Farrar-119">#cite_note-Farrar-119</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>119</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>  The tunnel is filled with soil and the toad hibernates in a small chamber at the end. During this time, urea accumulates in its tissues and water is drawn in from the surrounding damp soil by </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Osmosis">/wiki/Osmosis</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Osmosis</a>"&gt;</span><span>osmosis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> to supply the toad's needs.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Farrar_119-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Farrar-119">#cite_note-Farrar-119</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>119</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Spadefoot toads are "explosive breeders", all emerging from their burrows at the same time and converging on temporary pools, attracted to one of these by the calling of the first male to find a suitable breeding location.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-120</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-120">#cite_note-120</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>120</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2729"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The burrowing frogs of Australia have a rather different lifestyle. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Western_spotted_frog">/wiki/Western_spotted_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Western spotted frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>western spotted frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Heleioporus albopunctatus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) digs a burrow beside a river or in the bed of an ephemeral stream and regularly emerges to forage. Mating takes place and eggs are laid in a foam nest inside the burrow. The eggs partially develop there, but do not hatch until they are submerged following heavy rainfall. The tadpoles then swim out into the open water and rapidly complete their development.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-121</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-121">#cite_note-121</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>121</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Madagascan burrowing frogs are less fossorial and mostly bury themselves in leaf litter. One of these, the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scaphiophryne_marmorata">/wiki/Scaphiophryne_marmorata</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Scaphiophryne marmorata</a>"&gt;</span><span>green burrowing frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Scaphiophryne marmorata</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>), has a flattened head with a short snout and well-developed metatarsal tubercles on its hind feet to help with excavation. It also has greatly enlarged terminal discs on its fore feet that help it to clamber around in bushes.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-122</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-122">#cite_note-122</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>122</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>  It breeds in temporary pools that form after rains.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-123</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glass_frog">/wiki/Glass_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Glass frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>glass frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2734"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Tree frogs live high in the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Canopy_(biology)">/wiki/Canopy_(biology)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Canopy (biology)</a>"&gt;</span><span>canopy</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, where they scramble around on the branches, twigs, and leaves, sometimes never coming down to earth. The "true" tree frogs belong to the family Hylidae, but members of other frog families have independently adopted an arboreal habit, a case of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Convergent_evolution">/wiki/Convergent_evolution</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Convergent evolution</a>"&gt;</span><span>convergent evolution</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. These include the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glass_frogs">/wiki/Glass_frogs</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Glass frogs</a>"&gt;</span><span>glass frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (Centrolenidae), the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hyperoliidae">/wiki/Hyperoliidae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hyperoliidae</a>"&gt;</span><span>bush frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (Hyperoliidae), some of the narrow-mouthed frogs (Microhylidae), and the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhacophoridae">/wiki/Rhacophoridae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Rhacophoridae</a>"&gt;</span><span>shrub frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (Rhacophoridae).</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Britannica_111-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Britannica-111">#cite_note-Britannica-111</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>111</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Most tree frogs are under 10<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>cm (4<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>in) in length, with long legs and long toes with adhesive pads on the tips. The surface of the toe pads is formed from a closely packed layer of flat-topped, hexagonal </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Epidermis_(skin)">/wiki/Epidermis_(skin)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Epidermis (skin)</a>"&gt;</span><span>epidermal</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> cells separated by grooves into which glands secrete </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mucus">/wiki/Mucus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Mucus</a>"&gt;</span><span>mucus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. These toe pads, moistened by the mucus, provide the grip on any wet or dry surface, including glass. The forces involved include </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boundary_friction">/wiki/Boundary_friction</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Boundary friction</a>"&gt;</span><span>boundary friction</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> of the toe pad epidermis on the surface and also </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_tension">/wiki/Surface_tension</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Surface tension</a>"&gt;</span><span>surface tension</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viscosity">/wiki/Viscosity</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Viscosity</a>"&gt;</span><span>viscosity</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-124</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-124">#cite_note-124</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>124</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Tree frogs are very acrobatic and can catch insects while hanging by one toe from a twig or clutching onto the blade of a windswept reed.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-125</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-125">#cite_note-125</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>125</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Some members of the subfamily </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyllomedusinae">/wiki/Phyllomedusinae</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Phyllomedusinae</a>"&gt;</span><span>Phyllomedusinae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> have </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opposable_thumb#Opposition_and_apposition">/wiki/Opposable_thumb#Opposition_and_apposition</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Opposable thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span>opposable toes</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> on their feet. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phyllomedusa_ayeaye">/wiki/Phyllomedusa_ayeaye</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Phyllomedusa ayeaye</a>"&gt;</span><span>reticulated leaf frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Phyllomedusa ayeaye</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) has a single opposed </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digit_(anatomy)">/wiki/Digit_(anatomy)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Digit (anatomy)</a>"&gt;</span><span>digit</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> on each fore foot and two opposed digits on its hind feet. This allows it to grasp the stems of bushes as it clambers around in its riverside habitat.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-126</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-126">#cite_note-126</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>126</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2735"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2736"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Gliding</a>"&gt;</span><span>Gliding</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2737"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>During the evolutionary history of frogs, several different groups have independently taken to the air.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-127</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-127">#cite_note-127</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>127</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Some frogs in the tropical rainforest are specially adapted for gliding from tree to tree or parachuting to the forest floor. Typical of them is </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rhacophorus_nigropalmatus">/wiki/Rhacophorus_nigropalmatus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Rhacophorus nigropalmatus</a>"&gt;</span><span>Wallace's flying frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rhacophorus nigropalmatus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) from Malaysia and Borneo. It has large feet with the fingertips expanded into flat adhesive discs and the digits fully webbed. Flaps of skin occur on the lateral margins of the limbs and across the tail region. With the digits splayed, the limbs outstretched, and these flaps spread, it can glide considerable distances, but is unable to undertake powered flight.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-128</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-128">#cite_note-128</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>128</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> It can alter its direction of travel and navigate distances of up to 15<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>m (50<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#160;</span>ft) between trees.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-129</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-129">#cite_note-129</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span </span></span><span id="line2738"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2739"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading2</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h2</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Life_history</a>"&gt;</span><span>Life history</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h2</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2740"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size mw-halign-left</a>" <span class="attribute-name">typeof</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw:File/Thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-file-description</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">img</span> <span class="attribute-name">src</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Greenfrog_life_stages.svg/220px-Greenfrog_life_stages.svg.png">//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Greenfrog_life_stages.svg/220px-Greenfrog_life_stages.svg.png</a>" <span class="attribute-name">decoding</span>="<a class="attribute-value">async</a>" <span class="attribute-name">width</span>="<a class="attribute-value">220</a>" <span class="attribute-name">srcset</span>="<a class="attribute-value">//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Greenfrog_life_stages.svg/330px-Greenfrog_life_stages.svg.png 1.5x, class="attribute-value">1207</a>" <span class="attribute-name">data-file-height</span>="<a class="attribute-value">902</a>" <span>/</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span>Life cycle of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rana_clamitans">/wiki/Rana_clamitans</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Rana clamitans</a>"&gt;</span><span>green frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">br</span> <span>/</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana clamitans</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>)</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2741"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading3</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h3</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Reproduction</a>"&gt;</span><span>Reproduction</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h3</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2742"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Two main types of reproduction occur in frogs, prolonged breeding and explosive breeding. In the former, adopted by the majority of species, adult frogs  at certain times of year assemble at a pond, lake or stream to breed. Many frogs return to the bodies of water in which they developed as larvae. This often results in annual migrations involving thousands of individuals. In explosive breeders, mature adult frogs arrive at breeding sites in response to certain trigger factors such as rainfall occurring in an arid area. In these frogs, mating and spawning take place promptly and the speed of larval growth is rapid in order to make use of the ephemeral pools before they dry up.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins_130-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Stebbins-130">#cite_note-Stebbins-130</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>130</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2743"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Among prolonged breeders, males usually arrive at the breeding site first and remain there for some time whereas females tend to arrive later and depart soon after they have spawned. This means that males outnumber females at the water's edge and defend territories from which they expel other males. They advertise their presence by calling, often alternating their croaks with neighbouring frogs. Larger, stronger males tend to have deeper calls and maintain higher quality territories. Females select their mates at least partly on the basis of the depth of their voice.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-131</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-131">#cite_note-131</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>131</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>  In some species there are satellite males who have no territory and do not call. They may intercept females that are approaching a calling male or take over a vacated territory. Calling is an energy-sapping activity. Sometimes the two roles are reversed and a calling male gives up its territory and becomes a satellite.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins_130-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Stebbins-130">#cite_note-Stebbins-130</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>130</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2744"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2745"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size</a>" <span class="attribute-name">typeof</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw:File/Thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bufo_bufo_couple_during_migration(2005).jpg">/wiki/File:Bufo_bufo_couple_during_migration(2005).jpg</a>" <span </span></span><span id="line2746"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>In explosive breeders, the first male that finds a suitable breeding location, such as a temporary pool, calls loudly and other frogs of both sexes converge on the pool. Explosive breeders tend to call in unison creating a chorus that can be heard from far away. The spadefoot  toads (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scaphiopus">/wiki/Scaphiopus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Scaphiopus</a>"&gt;</span><span>Scaphiopus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> spp.</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) of North America fall into this category. Mate selection and courtship is not as important as speed in reproduction. In some years, suitable conditions may not occur and the frogs may go for two or more years without breeding.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins_130-2</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a </span></span><span id="line2747"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>At the breeding site, the male mounts the female and grips her tightly round the body. Typically, </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amplexus">/wiki/Amplexus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Amplexus</a>"&gt;</span><span>amplexus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> takes place in the water, the female releases her eggs and the male covers them with sperm; fertilisation is </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/External_fertilization">/wiki/External_fertilization</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">External fertilization</a>"&gt;</span><span>external</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. </span></span><span id="line2758"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>The larvae that emerge from the eggs are known as tadpoles (or occasionally polliwogs). Tadpoles lack eyelids and limbs, and have cartilaginous skeletons, gills for respiration (external gills at first, internal gills later), and tails they use for swimming.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Duellman_117-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Duellman-117">#cite_note-Duellman-117</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>117</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> As a general rule, free-living larvae are fully aquatic, but at least one species (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nannophrys_ceylonensis">/wiki/Nannophrys_ceylonensis</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Nannophrys ceylonensis</a>"&gt;</span><span>Nannophrys ceylonensis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) has semiterrestrial tadpoles which live among wet rocks.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-149</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-149">#cite_note-149</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span
