class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-150">#cite_note-150</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>150</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2759"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>From early in its development, a gill pouch covers the tadpole's gills and front legs. The lungs soon start to develop and are used as an accessory breathing organ. Some species go through metamorphosis while still inside the egg and hatch directly into small frogs. Tadpoles lack true teeth, but the jaws in most species have two elongated, parallel rows of small, </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keratin">/wiki/Keratin</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Keratin</a>"&gt;</span><span>keratinized</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> structures called keradonts in their upper jaws. Their lower jaws usually have three rows of keradonts surrounded by a horny beak, but the number of rows can vary and the exact arrangements of mouth parts provide a means for species identification.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins2_145-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Stebbins2-145">#cite_note-Stebbins2-145</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>145</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> In the Pipidae, with the exception of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hymenochirus">/wiki/Hymenochirus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hymenochirus</a>"&gt;</span><span>Hymenochirus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>, the tadpoles have paired anterior barbels, which make them resemble small </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Catfish">/wiki/Catfish</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Catfish</a>"&gt;</span><span>catfish</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Pipidae_116-1</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Pipidae-116">#cite_note-Pipidae-116</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>116</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Their tails are stiffened by a </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Notochord">/wiki/Notochord</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Notochord</a>"&gt;</span><span>notochord</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, but does not contain any bony or cartilaginous elements except for a few vertebrae at the base which forms the urostyle during metamorphosis. This has been suggested as an adaptation to their lifestyles; because the transformation into frogs happens very fast, the tail is made of soft tissue only, as bone and cartilage take a much longer time to be broken down and absorbed. The tail fin and tip is fragile and will easily tear, which is seen as an adaptation to escape from predators which try to grasp them by the tail.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-151</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-151">#cite_note-151</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>151</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2760"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Tadpoles are typically </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herbivore">/wiki/Herbivore</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Herbivore</a>"&gt;</span><span>herbivorous</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, feeding mostly on </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alga">/wiki/Alga</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Alga</a>"&gt;</span><span>algae</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, including </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diatom">/wiki/Diatom</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Diatom</a>"&gt;</span><span>diatoms</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> filtered from the water through the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gill">/wiki/Gill</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Gill</a>"&gt;</span><span>gills</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Some species are carnivorous at the tadpole stage, eating insects, smaller tadpoles, and fish. The Cuban tree frog (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Osteopilus septentrionalis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) is one of a number of species in which the tadpoles can be </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cannibalism">/wiki/Cannibalism</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cannibalism</a>"&gt;</span><span>cannibalistic</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Tadpoles that develop legs early may be eaten by the others, so late developers may have better long-term survival prospects.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-152</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-152">#cite_note-152</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>152</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2761"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Tadpoles are highly vulnerable to being eaten by fish, </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Newt">/wiki/Newt</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Newt</a>"&gt;</span><span>newts</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, predatory </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diving_beetle">/wiki/Diving_beetle</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Diving beetle</a>"&gt;</span><span>diving beetles</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, and birds, particularly </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Water_bird">/wiki/Water_bird</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Water bird</a>"&gt;</span><span>water birds</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, such as </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stork">/wiki/Stork</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Stork</a>"&gt;</span><span>storks</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heron">/wiki/Heron</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Heron</a>"&gt;</span><span>herons</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Domestic_duck">/wiki/Domestic_duck</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Domestic duck</a>"&gt;</span><span>domestic ducks</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Some tadpoles, including those of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cane_toad">/wiki/Cane_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Cane toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>cane toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rhinella marina</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>), are poisonous. The tadpole stage may be as short as a week in explosive breeders or it may last through one or more winters followed by metamorphosis in the spring.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-153</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-153">#cite_note-153</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>153</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2762"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2763"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading4</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h4</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Metamorphosis</a>"&gt;</span><span>Metamorphosis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h4</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2764"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>At the end of the tadpole stage, a frog undergoes metamorphosis in which its body makes a sudden transition into the adult form. This metamorphosis typically lasts only 24 hours, and is initiated by production of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hormone">/wiki/Hormone</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Hormone</a>"&gt;</span><span>hormone</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thyroxine">/wiki/Thyroxine</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Thyroxine</a>"&gt;</span><span>thyroxine</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. This causes different tissues to develop in different ways. The principal changes that take place include the development of the lungs and the disappearance of the gills and gill pouch, making the front legs visible. The lower jaw transforms into the big mandible of the carnivorous adult, and the long, spiral gut of the herbivorous tadpole is replaced by the typical short gut of a predator.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins2_145-2</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Stebbins2-145">#cite_note-Stebbins2-145</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>145</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Homeostatic feedback control of food intake is largely absent, making tadpoles eat constantly when food is present. But shortly before and during metamorphosis the sensation of hunger is suppressed, and they stop eating while their gut and internal organs are reorganised and prepared for a different diet.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-154</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-154">#cite_note-154</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>154</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-155</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-155">#cite_note-155</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>155</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Also the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gut_microbiota">/wiki/Gut_microbiota</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Gut microbiota</a>"&gt;</span><span>gut microbiota</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> changes, from being similar to that of fish to resembling that of amniotes.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-156</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-156">#cite_note-156</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>156</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Exceptions are carnivorous tadpoles like </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lepidobatrachus_laevis">/wiki/Lepidobatrachus_laevis</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Lepidobatrachus laevis</a>"&gt;</span><span>Lepidobatrachus laevis</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, which has a gut already adapted to a diet similar to that of adults. These continue to eat during metamorphosis.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-157</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-157">#cite_note-157</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>157</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The nervous system becomes adapted for hearing and stereoscopic vision, and for new methods of locomotion and feeding.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins2_145-3</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Stebbins2-145">#cite_note-Stebbins2-145</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>145</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The eyes are repositioned higher up on the head and the eyelids and associated glands are formed. The eardrum, middle ear, and inner ear are developed. The skin becomes thicker and tougher, the lateral line system is lost, and skin glands are developed.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Stebbins2_145-4</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Stebbins2-145">#cite_note-Stebbins2-145</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>145</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The final stage is the disappearance of the tail, but this takes place rather later, the tissue being used to produce a spurt of growth in the limbs.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-158</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-158">#cite_note-158</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>158</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Frogs are at their most vulnerable to predators when they are undergoing metamorphosis. At this time, the tail is being lost and locomotion by means of limbs is only just becoming established.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Britannica_111-2</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Britannica-111">#cite_note-Britannica-111</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>111</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>

class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Euphlyctis hexadactylus</a>"&gt;</span><span>Euphlyctis hexadactylus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>, with plants constituting 79.5% of its diet by volume.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-166</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>  Many frogs use their sticky tongues to catch prey, while others simply grab them with their mouths.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-167</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Adult frogs are themselves attacked by many predators. The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>northern leopard frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>168</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span </span></span><span id="line2783"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2784"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size mw-halign-left</a>" <span class="attribute-name">typeof</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw:File/Thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:TrophicWeb.jpg">/wiki/File:TrophicWeb.jpg</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-file-description</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">img</span> <span class="attribute-name">alt</span>="<a class="attribute-value"></a>" <span class="attribute-name">src</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/TrophicWeb.jpg/220px-TrophicWeb.jpg">//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/TrophicWeb.jpg/220px-TrophicWeb.jpg</a>" <span class="attribute-name">decoding</span>="<a class="attribute-value">async</a>" <span class="attribute-name">width</span>="<a class="attribute-value">220</a>" <span class="attribute-name">height</span>="<a class="attribute-value">91</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-file-element</a>" <span class="attribute-name">srcset</span>="<a class="attribute-value">//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/TrophicWeb.jpg/330px-TrophicWeb.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/13/TrophicWeb.jpg/440px-TrophicWeb.jpg 2x</a>" <span class="attribute-name">data-file-width</span>="<a class="attribute-value">3260</a>" <span class="attribute-name">data-file-height</span>="<a class="attribute-value">1350</a>" <span>/</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span>A trophic pyramid showing frogs as primary predators</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2785"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Frogs are primary predators and an important part of the </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Food_web">/wiki/Food_web</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Food web</a>"&gt;</span><span>food web</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. Being </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ectotherm">/wiki/Ectotherm</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Ectotherm</a>"&gt;</span><span>cold-blooded</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, they make efficient use of the food they eat with little energy being used for metabolic processes, while the rest is transformed into </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biomass_(ecology)">/wiki/Biomass_(ecology)</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Biomass (ecology)</a>"&gt;</span><span>biomass</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. They are themselves eaten by secondary predators and are the primary terrestrial consumers of invertebrates, most of which feed on plants. By reducing herbivory, they play a part in increasing the growth of plants and are thus part of a delicately balanced ecosystem.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-169</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-169">#cite_note-169</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>169</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2786"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Little is known about the longevity of frogs and toads in the wild, but some can live for many years. </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Skeletochronology">/wiki/Skeletochronology</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Skeletochronology</a>"&gt;</span><span>Skeletochronology</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> is a method of examining bones to determine age. Using this method, the ages of </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mountain_yellow-legged_frog">/wiki/Mountain_yellow-legged_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Mountain yellow-legged frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>mountain yellow-legged frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana muscosa</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) were studied, the phalanges of the toes showing seasonal lines where growth slows in winter. The oldest frogs had ten bands, so their age was believed to be 14 years, including the four-year tadpole stage.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-170</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-170">#cite_note-170</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>170</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Captive frogs and toads have been recorded as living for up to 40 years, an age achieved by a European common toad (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Bufo bufo</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>). The cane toad (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rhinella marina</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) has been known to survive 24 years in captivity, and the American bullfrog (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana catesbeiana</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) 14 years.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-171</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-171">#cite_note-171</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>171</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Frogs from temperate climates hibernate during the winter, and four species are known to be able to withstand freezing during this time, including the wood frog (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rana sylvatica</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>).</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-172</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>172</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a </span></span><span id="line2787"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>

class="attribute-value">Pouched frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Pouched frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span </span></span><span id="line2791"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Although care of offspring is poorly understood in frogs,  up to an estimated 20% of amphibian species may care for their young in some way.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-173</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-173">#cite_note-173</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>173</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution_of_biparental_care_in_tropical_frogs">/wiki/Evolution_of_biparental_care_in_tropical_frogs</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Evolution of biparental care in tropical frogs</a>"&gt;</span><span>evolution of parental care</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> in frogs is driven primarily by the size of the water body in which they breed. Those that breed in smaller water bodies tend to have greater and more complex parental care behaviour.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Brown1_174-0</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Brown1-174">#cite_note-Brown1-174</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>174</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Because predation of eggs and larvae is high in large water bodies, some frog species started to lay their eggs on land. Once this happened, the desiccating terrestrial environment demands that one or both parents keep them moist to ensure their survival.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-175</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-175">#cite_note-175</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>175</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The subsequent need to transport hatched tadpoles to a water body required an even more intense form of parental care.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Brown1_174-1</a>" <span </span></span><span id="line2792"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>In small pools, predators are mostly absent and  competition between tadpoles becomes the variable that constrains their survival. Certain frog species avoid this competition by making use of smaller </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phytotelma">/wiki/Phytotelma</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Phytotelma</a>"&gt;</span><span>phytotelmata</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (water-filled leaf </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/axil">https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/axil</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">extiw</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">wikt:axil</a>"&gt;</span><span>axils</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> or small woody cavities) as sites for depositing a few tadpoles.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-176</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-176">#cite_note-176</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>176</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>  While these smaller rearing sites are free from competition, they also lack sufficient nutrients to support a tadpole without parental assistance. Frog species that changed from the use of larger to smaller phytotelmata have evolved a strategy of providing their offspring with nutritive but unfertilised eggs.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-Brown1_174-2</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-Brown1-174">#cite_note-Brown1-174</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>174</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The female </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Strawberry_poison-dart_frog">/wiki/Strawberry_poison-dart_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Strawberry poison-dart frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>strawberry poison-dart frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Oophaga pumilio</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) lays her eggs on the forest floor. The male frog guards them from predation and carries water in his cloaca to keep them moist. When they hatch, the female moves the tadpoles on her back to a water-holding </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bromeliad">/wiki/Bromeliad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Bromeliad</a>"&gt;</span><span>bromeliad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> or other similar water body, depositing just one in each location. She visits them regularly and feeds them by laying one or two unfertilised eggs in the phytotelma, continuing to do this until the young are large enough to undergo metamorphosis.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-177</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-177">#cite_note-177</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>177</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granular_poison_frog">/wiki/Granular_poison_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Granular poison frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>granular poison frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Oophaga granulifera</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) looks after its tadpoles in a similar way.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-178</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-178">#cite_note-178</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>178</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2793"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Many other diverse forms of parental care are seen in frogs. The tiny male </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Colostethus_subpunctatus">/wiki/Colostethus_subpunctatus</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Colostethus subpunctatus</a>"&gt;</span><span>Colostethus subpunctatus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span> stands guard over his egg cluster, laid under a stone or log. When the eggs hatch, he transports the tadpoles on his back to a temporary pool, where he partially immerses himself in the water and one or more tadpoles drop off. He then moves on to another pool.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-179</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-179">#cite_note-179</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>179</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The male </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Common_midwife_toad">/wiki/Common_midwife_toad</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Common midwife toad</a>"&gt;</span><span>common midwife toad</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Alytes obstetricans</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) carries the eggs around with him attached to his hind legs. He keeps them damp in dry weather by immersing himself in a pond, and prevents them from getting too wet in soggy vegetation by raising his hindquarters. After three to six weeks, he travels to a pond and the eggs hatch into tadpoles.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-180</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-180">#cite_note-180</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>180</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tungara_frog">/wiki/Tungara_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Tungara frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>tungara frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Physalaemus pustulosus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) builds a floating nest from foam to protect its eggs from predation. The foam is made from </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein">/wiki/Protein</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Protein</a>"&gt;</span><span>proteins</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> and </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lectin">/wiki/Lectin</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Lectin</a>"&gt;</span><span>lectins</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, and seems to have antimicrobial properties.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-181</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-181">#cite_note-181</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>181</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> Several pairs of frogs may form a colonial nest on a previously built raft. The eggs are laid in the centre, followed by  alternate layers of foam and eggs, finishing with a foam capping.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-182</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-182">#cite_note-182</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>182</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2794"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>Some frogs protect their offspring inside their own bodies. Both male and female </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pouched_frog">/wiki/Pouched_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Pouched frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>pouched frogs</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Assa darlingtoni</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) guard their eggs, which are laid on the ground. When the eggs hatch, the male lubricates his body with the jelly surrounding them and immerses himself in the egg mass. The tadpoles wriggle into skin pouches on his side, where they develop until they metamorphose into juvenile frogs.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-183</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-183">#cite_note-183</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>183</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The female </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gastric-brooding_frog">/wiki/Gastric-brooding_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Gastric-brooding frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>gastric-brooding frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rheobatrachus</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span> sp.) from </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia">/wiki/Australia</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Australia</a>"&gt;</span><span>Australia</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>, now probably extinct, swallows her fertilised eggs, which then develop inside her stomach. She ceases to feed and stops secreting </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stomach_acid">/wiki/Stomach_acid</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Stomach acid</a>"&gt;</span><span>stomach acid</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span>. The tadpoles rely on the yolks of the eggs for nourishment. After six or seven weeks, they are ready for metamorphosis. The mother regurgitates the tiny frogs, which hop away from her mouth.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-184</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-184">#cite_note-184</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>184</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span> The female </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Darwin%27s_frog">/wiki/Darwin%27s_frog</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Darwin<span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#39;</span>s frog</a>"&gt;</span><span>Darwin's frog</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> (</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>Rhinoderma darwinii</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span>) from </span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chile">/wiki/Chile</a>" <span class="attribute-name">title</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Chile</a>"&gt;</span><span>Chile</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span> lays up to 40 eggs on the ground, where they are guarded by the male. When the tadpoles are about to hatch, they are engulfed by the male, which carries them around inside his much-enlarged vocal sac. Here they are immersed in a frothy, viscous liquid that contains some nourishment to supplement what they obtain from the yolks of the eggs. They remain in the sac for seven to ten weeks before undergoing metamorphosis, after which they move into the male's mouth and emerge.</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">sup</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite_ref-185</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">reference</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frog#cite_note-185">#cite_note-185</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#91;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span>185</span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">span</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">cite-bracket</a>"&gt;</span><span><span class="entity"><span>&amp;</span>#93;</span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">span</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">sup</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2795"><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">p</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2796"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">div</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-heading mw-heading2</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">h2</span> <span class="attribute-name">id</span>="<a class="attribute-value">Defence</a>"&gt;</span><span>Defence</span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">h2</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">div</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2797"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size</a>" <span class="start-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranitomeya_imitator">/wiki/Ranitomeya_imitator</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-redirect</a>" <span class="end-tag">a</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">i</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figcaption</span>&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;/<span class="end-tag">figure</span>&gt;</span><span>
</span></span><span id="line2798"><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">figure</span> <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw-default-size</a>" <span class="attribute-name">typeof</span>="<a class="attribute-value">mw:File/Thumb</a>"&gt;</span><span></span><span>&lt;<span class="start-tag">a</span> <span class="attribute-name">href</span>="<a class="attribute-value" href="view-source:https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Dendrobates_pumilio.jpg">/wiki/File:Dendrobates_pumilio.jpg</a>" <span class="attribute-name">class</span>="<a
